# Brief — I-qgen-001: Query-Generation Bake-off (first instance of the standard pipeline-section review, GH #1291)

REVIEW THIS PLAN for soundness (this is a brief/plan gate, NOT a code gate). Judge whether the methodology will produce a TRUSTWORTHY, decision-grade result and whether the acceptance criteria are correct. Do NOT run anything.

## Goal
Empirically decide which query-generation MECHANISM POLARIS should secure in its closed-loop coverage front-end, by bake-off on the locked benchmark set, on GLM-5.2, in VMs, faithfulness engine untouched.

## Context (verified this session; see docs/session_2026_06_22_diagnosis_and_querygen_frontier.md)
- POLARIS's live query-gen = template/planner "amplified facets", verified TWO steps behind the closed-loop frontier (STORM is wired but PG_STORM_ENABLED_IN_BENCHMARK=0). Query-gen is the highest-leverage stage (it decides coverage; everything downstream is capped by it).
- The drb_72 disaster invalidated the last benchmark run via wrong-question + split-brain-scoring + Title-only-stub bugs. Those MUST be fixed before any score is trusted.

## Candidates (2026 patterns named by operator) + REQUIRED baselines
- 2026 candidates: AgentCPM-Report/WARP (open 8B, arXiv 2602.06540), DuMate (2606.07299), FS-Researcher (2602.01566), ScaffoldAgent (2606.20122).
- VERIFIED 2025 baselines (MUST be in the bake-off, else we pick "best of 4" when a 2025 system may beat all four): IterResearch/Tongyi (2510.24701/2511.07327, open-weight), WebWeaver (2509.13312), ConvergeWriter (2509.12811).
- FLOOR baseline: current POLARIS template-facets behaviour.

## Operative metric
- Coverage PRIMARY: DeepResearch Bench II info_recall + DeepResearch Bench v1 RACE.
- Faithfulness WATCHED (must not regress): DEER + DeepTRACE + DeepScholar-Bench sentence-verifiability.
- A candidate that lifts coverage but regresses faithfulness LOSES — POLARIS identity is faithfulness.

## Plan (the standard process, applied)
- GATE 0 (precondition): fix + sanity-canary the benchmark harness — right question launched, packed-question == answered-question, Title-only stubs rejected. Canary must pass on a known report BEFORE any bake-off scoring. This is a hard blocker.
- STEP A: confirm candidate RUNNABILITY — which of the 7 (4 candidates + 3 baselines) have runnable open code adaptable to GLM-5.2. Unrunnable ones are documented, not faked. (AgentCPM/WebWeaver/IterResearch/ConvergeWriter are open; DuMate/FS-Researcher/ScaffoldAgent runnability to confirm.)
- STEP B: VM bake-off — each RUNNABLE candidate × a stratified benchmark SUBSET (e.g. 10-15 tasks across themes) × GLM-5.2, parallel across VMs. Score both axes. Screening ranks them.
- STEP C: FINALS — full benchmark eval on the top 1-2.
- STEP D: §-1.1 line-by-line audit of the winning output (data + human quality), not a leaderboard number alone.
- STEP E: decision → open the "port winner into POLARIS closed-loop front-end" brief (Codex diff-gated); faithfulness engine untouched.

## What to check (the bar)
- Is GATE 0 sufficient to prevent another drb_72? Are the three harness bugs the RIGHT precondition, or is one missing?
- Is the candidate+baseline set correct — is it a real decision (baselines + floor included), not a best-of-4?
- Is the metric correct — coverage primary, faithfulness watched, and is "regresses faithfulness => loses" the right rule?
- Is the standalone-bake-off-to-select-then-port framing honest (the standalone number selects the mechanism; the integrated POLARIS run decides)?
- Is the acceptance (behavioural effect in real output + §-1.1 audit, not green tests) correctly the §-1.4 standard?
- Any P0/P1 execution risk that would make the result untrustworthy or the decision wrong.

